    hardscapeStylePara: "NYC hardscape style runs to bluestone patios with Belgian-block edging in brownstone yards, precast unit pavers in Queens and Staten Island single-family, and boardwalk-style pressure-treated decks in Brooklyn rowhome gardens. Cast-iron garden furniture is period-correct for Park Slope and Brooklyn Heights Victorian-era lots. Permeable-paver driveways are encouraged under NYC DEP stormwater rules and qualify for the Green Infrastructure Grant Program up to $25,000.",
    lawnMaterialPara: "Cool-season fescue blends (Kentucky 31, Pennington Dense Shade) dominate NYC residential lawns because of the shade load from street trees and four-story building shadows. Kentucky bluegrass is used on sunny Staten Island and Bronx Riverdale tracts. Zoysia is not viable because the winter dormancy leaves yards brown November through April. Tall fescue is increasingly specified on Queens and Brooklyn corner lots because it handles both drought and shade.",
    turfAndXeriscapeRebatesPara: "NYC does not offer turf-replacement rebates the way western cities do, but the NYC DEP Green Infrastructure Grant Program funds permeable pavement, green roofs, and rain gardens at properties over 3 acres. NYC Parks' MillionTreesNYC legacy continues to provide discounted tree installations through the Parks and Tree Fund. NYSERDA landscape-scale grants for Long Island properties offer up to $100,000 for drought-tolerant and stormwater-capture installations.",
    invasivePestPara: "Spotted lanternfly (Lycorma delicatula) is the dominant regional invasive pest as of 2024-2026; NYS DEC mandates public reporting and host-plant (tree of heaven, Ailanthus altissima) removal. Emerald ash borer has killed nearly every mature ash in the five boroughs. Oak wilt has not yet reached NYC but asian longhorned beetle quarantine zones persist in parts of Queens. Hemlock woolly adelgid affects Central and Prospect Park ornamentals but less so outer-borough yards.",
    HOAAestheticPara: "NYC has essentially no HOA landscape restrictions because co-ops and condos rarely have individual outdoor space. Exceptions are gated communities in Forest Hills Gardens, Sea Gate, and Silver Lake (Staten Island) where architectural covenants apply. Brooklyn Heights Association and Park Slope Civic Council enforce peer-reviewed character standards on visible-from-street front yards. Historic Districts Council review layers on top for landmarked blocks.",
