    turfAndXeriscapeRebatesPara: "Houston does not offer direct turf-replacement rebates the way western cities do, but the Bayou City Waterways program funds green-infrastructure projects in targeted watersheds. Harris County Flood Control District cost-shares rain gardens and detention on lots over 5,000 sqft. The West Houston Association and Memorial Park Conservancy run separate sustainability-incentive programs. Smart-controller rebates under the City of Houston WaterSmart program pay $50-$200.",
    invasivePestPara: "Red imported fire ants (Solenopsis invicta) are the dominant Houston yard pest; Over-and-Out bait and Extinguish Plus are the standard mound-treatment products. Chinch bugs (Blissus insularis) attack St Augustine lawns in drought-stress periods. Formosan subterranean termite infestations affect woody plantings and hardscape structures. Emerald ash borer was confirmed in Harris County in 2023; Texas A&M AgriLife Extension tracks spread. Crape myrtle bark scale is a growing ornamental concern.",
    HOAAestheticPara: "Houston has no municipal zoning but deed restrictions in River Oaks, West University Place, Bellaire, and Memorial Villages function as private-HOA rules. Texas Property Code 202.007 protects drought-tolerant landscaping against HOA turf-required covenants. The Woodlands Township has detailed tree-preservation rules enforced through the Woodlands Community Association. Kingwood and Clear Lake master-planned communities have color palettes and foundation-planting requirements specific to deed-restricted areas.",
    treeServicePara: "Houston's heritage oak, pine, and pecan canopy is protected under the Tree and Shrub Ordinance (Chapter 33 of Code of Ordinances); any removal of a protected tree over 8 inches DBH requires a permit. Licensed arborists through ISA or TCIA charge $800-$3,500 per mature tree removal. Post-hurricane cleanup (Harvey 2017, Beryl 2024) spikes pricing 40-60 percent. The Trees for Houston nonprofit subsidizes tree replacement on residential lots. Pine beetle and oak wilt monitoring drives preventive treatments.",
    seasonalMaintenancePara: "Houston landscape maintenance runs year-round. Warm-season grass greens up in March and peaks June-September. Fall overseed with annual ryegrass extends green cover through winter on some neighborhoods. Pre-emergent weed control applications happen late-February and late-September. Hurricane-season debris cleanup (June-November) creates episodic workload spikes. Freeze protection on tropical plantings (Uri-level events) drove many homeowners to replace frost-tender species with native hardy alternatives.",
    stormwaterPara: "Harris County Flood Control District Detention Policy requires on-site detention for any residential project adding over 5,000 sqft of impervious cover. Post-Harvey updates to the Atlas 14 rainfall standards increased detention sizing requirements. The City of Houston Green Building Resource Center incentivizes permeable paving and bioretention. Rain-garden and bioswale installations qualify for Harris County Flood Control cost-share up to $2,500. Drainage district-specific rules vary across the metro.",
    commonScamPara: "The dominant Houston landscaping scam is the post-hurricane tree-removal crew that offers $800-$2,000 cash prices for emergency work, demands payment up front, and disappears. Texas Department of Licensing and Regulation (TDLR) does not license general landscape contractors, but TDLR-licensed irrigators (LI license) are required for any permitted irrigation install. Unlicensed irrigation work violates TCEQ Chapter 344 and is unenforceable. Verify LI license number and insurance before cash changes hands."
